# Gateway — Kong implementation guide

Source: Archive/Development/Backend/ChangeRequest/Request-001 ("Implement Kong gateway"). Design decisions this implementation follows, not re-derives: Archive/Architecture/ARCHITECTURE.md §6 (external API surface), §7 (security at the gateway), §11 (build layout — reserves `gateway/kong.decl.yaml`). Endpoint inventory: Archive/Development/Backend/Phase/Phase-1 through Phase-7. Change log with per-decision rationale: Archive/Development/Backend/ChangeLog/Gateway. Real issues hit and fixed while building this: Archive/Issues/Gateway0.

Everything below is either a decision ARCHITECTURE.md already locked in (cited as such), or a judgment call this implementation had to make because neither ARCHITECTURE.md nor BUSINESS_RULES.md specifies it (also called out as such, explicitly).

---

## 1. What was built

Two new files carry the actual gateway behavior:

- `gateway/kong.decl.yaml` — Kong's entire routing/security config, in DB-less/declarative form. This is the reserved path from ARCHITECTURE.md §11.
- `gateway/docker-entrypoint.sh` — a ~40-line render step that runs before Kong starts (see §4 below for why it exists at all).

Plus `gateway/keys/.gitkeep` (placeholder so the directory exists before the real key does) and one change to `docker-compose.yml` (a new `kong` service). Full file-by-file rationale is in the change log; this document is the "what/why/how to verify" narrative.

### 1.1 Routing

Every service+route in `gateway/kong.decl.yaml` traces back to a specific line in a specific Phase file. The full inventory extracted from Phase-1 through Phase-7:

| Method + path | Service | Auth required? | Source |
|---|---|---|---|
| `POST /api/auth/register` | identity-service | No | Phase-1 |
| `POST /api/auth/login` | identity-service | No | Phase-1 |
| `GET /api/users/me` | identity-service | Yes | Phase-2 |
| `PATCH /api/users/me` | identity-service | Yes | Phase-2 |
| `GET /api/users/{id}` (admin only) | identity-service | Yes | Phase-2 |
| `PATCH /api/users/{id}/status` (admin only) | identity-service | Yes | Phase-2 |
| `PATCH /api/users/{id}/role` (admin only) | identity-service | Yes | Phase-2 |
| `POST /api/products` (admin only) | catalog-service | Yes | Phase-3 |
| `GET /api/products` | catalog-service | **No** (public browsing, CAT-006) | Phase-3 |
| `GET /api/products/{id}` | catalog-service | **No** (public browsing, CAT-006) | Phase-3 |
| `PATCH /api/products/{id}` (admin only) | catalog-service | Yes | Phase-4 |
| `PATCH /api/products/{id}/status` (admin only) | catalog-service | Yes | Phase-4 |
| `DELETE /api/products/{id}` (admin only) | catalog-service | Yes | Phase-4 |
| `POST /api/orders` | order-service | Yes | Phase-5 |
| `GET /api/orders/{id}` | order-service | Yes | Phase-5 |
| `GET /api/orders` | order-service | Yes | Phase-5 |
| `POST /api/orders/{id}/cancel` | order-service | Yes | Phase-6 |
| `GET /api/notifications` | notification-service | Yes | Phase-7 |

18 method+path pairs, expressed as 17 Kong routes (`GET`/`PATCH /api/users/me` share one route object with two methods). This matches ARCHITECTURE.md §6's path-prefix table (`/api/auth/*`,`/api/users/*` → identity-service; `/api/products/*` → catalog-service; `/api/orders/*` → order-service; `/api/notifications/*` → notification-service), just at the granularity Kong actually needs (method + exact/regex path, not a prose prefix rule).

Every service's `url:` in `kong.decl.yaml` (`http://identity-service:8081`, `http://catalog-service:8082`, `http://order-service:8083`, `http://notification-service:8084`) uses the port each service's own `application.yml` declares (`server.port`), and a bare hostname matching that service's directory/module name — the hostname a future docker-compose entry for that service is expected to register on the shared default network, per this file's own existing convention (every other service in `docker-compose.yml` is reachable by its compose service-key name). **Those four services are not yet in `docker-compose.yml`** — adding them is not part of this change (out of scope: "do not touch identity-service/, catalog-service/, order-service/, notification-service/", and no docker-compose entry for them exists to modify either). Until they're added, Kong will return `503 Service Unavailable` for every route (confirmed in §5 below) — that's Kong correctly trying to proxy to a hostname that doesn't resolve yet, not a bug in this config.

### 1.2 What Kong enforces, and what it deliberately does not

Kong verifies **identity** (a request's JWT has a valid RS256 signature from `identity-service`'s keypair and hasn't expired) on every route except the two that can't require one. It does **not** decide **authorization** for `(admin only)` routes — ARCHITECTURE.md §7 describes Kong forwarding `X-Consumer-*`/claims headers and services trusting them, and Phase-1 says explicitly: "Kong (or, until Kong's policy is wired up, the service itself as a stopgap) rejects the caller unless the forwarded role claim is ADMIN" — the `roles.code` value actually seeded by the database, not "ADMINISTRATOR" (the business-rules prose term for the same role), a mismatch Phase-1/Phase-2 originally had and the identity-service implementation caught. No Kong ACL/role-based-access plugin is configured in this change — that's a real scope boundary, not an oversight: enforcing it in Kong would mean encoding BUSINESS_RULES.md's role logic into gateway config, duplicating what each service already has to implement anyway for its own internal consistency (e.g. an admin promoting another admin still needs the service to check the actor's role against its own database, not just trust a header). Each service must check the forwarded role claim itself for every `(admin only)` endpoint.

